londonGrill.description:
London Grill is a modern restaurant-bar web application with a full ordering cycle.

London Grill is a full-featured SPA for a restaurant-bar that demonstrates a comprehensive approach to building modern web interfaces. The project combines premium-style visual design with strong business logic: from a multi-level menu to authentication and order management.

Implemented functionality:

Dynamic menu system:
- multi-level tab navigation with drink categories (cocktails, infusions, wines, beer) and food categories (burgers, snacks);
- automatic item generation from assets folder structure via Vite glob imports;
- filtering by groups and subcategories with smooth transitions;
- product cards with images, prices, volumes, and add-to-cart button.

Complete cart and ordering flow:
- quantity management (increment/decrement);
- data persistence via localStorage with auto-sync;
- real-time total price calculation;
- table selection interface via custom dropdown;
- header cart indicator with badge counter.

Firebase authentication:
- sign-up and sign-in via email/password;
- protected routes (cart is available only for authorized users);
- real-time auth status tracking via onAuthStateChanged;
- logout button with current user email display.

Internationalization (i18n):
- EN/RU language switch without page reload;
- full UI localization via context provider;
- support for dynamic translations for auto-generated menu content.

Interactive events slider:
- custom promo slider with left/right navigation;
- smooth CSS slide transition animations;
- adaptive event cards with images and descriptions.

Landing page with hero section:
- large hero block with clear CTA elements;
- highlights section with key advantages;
- decorative elements (glow effects, patterns) for visual depth.

Notification system:
- ToastProvider for status messages (success, error, info);
- automatic hide via timeout;
- adaptive positioning for mobile devices.

Key technical solutions:

Architecture and state management:
- React with functional components and hooks;
- MobX for reactive global cart state management;
- Context API for i18n and toast system;
- React Router v6 with dynamic navigation and protected routes.

Styling and UX:
- CSS Modules for component-level style isolation;
- custom design system with CSS variables (sage/gold/warm palette);
- responsive design via media queries and flexible grid/flexbox layouts;
- smooth transitions and animations (fade, slide, hover effects);
- image optimization with lazy loading and async decoding.

Performance and optimization:
- Vite for instant HMR and optimized production builds;
- useMemo for caching heavy computations (dynamic menu generation);
- useCallback for memoizing event handlers;
- dynamic image imports via glob patterns.

Firebase integration:
- Firebase Authentication with email/password provider;
- secure config storage via environment variables (.env);
- auth error handling with user-facing notifications.

Code quality:
- ESLint for static code analysis;
- Prettier for consistent formatting;
- configured ignore files to exclude build artifacts.

Deployment:
- project is configured for automatic deployment via Vercel with SPA routing support;
- vercel.json configuration for correct client-side route handling;
- use of environment variables for sensitive Firebase data.

cyberX.description:
CyberX Food Mini App is a TypeScript-based food ordering application designed with future Telegram Mini Apps integration in mind.

CyberX is an advanced SPA for food ordering, built on a modern TypeScript stack with an architecture prepared for integration into the Telegram Mini Apps ecosystem. The project demonstrates a strong understanding of type safety, Redux Toolkit state management, and scalable web application development with a focus on UX and testing.

Implemented functionality:

Auth-gated architecture:
- full app protection via Firebase Authentication (email/password);
- protected routes using a ProtectedRoute HOC component;
- automatic auth state tracking via onAuthStateChanged;
- conditional UI rendering based on authorization status;
- redirect of unauthorized users to the login page.

Dynamic categorized menu:
- menu data loading from external API (mockapi.io) via Redux Toolkit createAsyncThunk;
- category filtering (Breakfast, Dinner, Dessert) with smooth transitions;
- "See more" pagination for progressive content loading;
- detailed dish overlay with full description;
- interactive quantity counter inside modal window;
- adaptive card grid via CSS Grid with auto-fit.

Advanced cart with Redux Toolkit:
- centralized cart state management via cartSlice;
- automatic totalQuantity and totalAmount recalculation on changes;
- increment/decrement handling for item quantity;
- remove individual items and clear entire cart;
- immutable operations powered by Immer (built into RTK);
- typed action creators and selectors.

Theme system:
- Light / Dark / System mode switching;
- automatic system theme detection via prefers-color-scheme;
- reactive theme updates on system preference changes;
- CSS variables for all color tokens;
- smooth transitions when changing theme;
- persistent theme selection between sessions.

i18next internationalization:
- centralized translation management via react-i18next;
- support for dynamic keys for categories and menu items;
- ready for scaling to multiple languages;
- typed translation keys via TypeScript.

Playwright E2E testing:
- configured Playwright for automated tests;
- coverage of critical user scenarios;
- configuration prepared for CI/CD integration.

Telegram Mini Apps readiness:
- architecture prepared for future Telegram initData auth integration;
- environment variable support for VITE_TELEGRAM_AUTH_ENDPOINT;
- compatibility with browser and future Telegram WebView.

Key technical solutions:

TypeScript and type safety:
- broad TypeScript coverage across the codebase (70.6%);
- strict typing for Redux state, actions, and reducers;
- typed useAppDispatch and useAppSelector hooks;
- interfaces for component props and API responses;
- custom type definitions for asset imports (.svg, .png, .jpg);
- typed environment variables via ImportMetaEnv.

Redux Toolkit state management:
- cart and menu slices with auto-generated reducers;
- async thunks for asynchronous operations (fetchMenuItems);
- normalized state structure for optimal access;
- extraReducers for loading/fulfilled/rejected handling;
- typed RootState and AppDispatch for hook inference.

Component architecture:
- feature-based structure (MenuPage, CartPage, LoginPage);
- context providers for Auth and Theme;
- custom hooks for business logic encapsulation (useMenu, useCart, useLogin);
- presentational components with clear prop interfaces;
- composition via children props in providers.

Routing and navigation:
- React Router v6 with typed ROUTES constants;
- protected routes through ProtectedRoute wrapper;
- programmatic navigation via useNavigate;
- automatic redirects based on authentication status;
- BASE_URL support for subdirectory deployment.

Styling and design system:
- CSS Custom Properties for centralized design tokens;
- data-theme attribute for dynamic theming;
- modular CSS with BEM-like methodology;
- backdrop-filter for glassmorphism effects;
- responsive design via media queries and fluid typography;
- animations via CSS keyframes for smooth transitions;
- radial gradients for atmospheric background.

Performance optimization:
- lazy loading for menu images;
- optimized build with Vite;
- tree-shaking through ES modules;
- reduced rerenders via proper state structure;
- CSS containment to isolate layout thrashing.

Firebase integration:
- modular Firebase SDK v12 initialization;
- secure credential storage via environment variables;
- auth error handling with user-friendly notifications;
- cleanup functions for auth listener unsubscription.

Developer Experience:
- strict TypeScript configuration (tsconfig.json);
- Vite for instant hot module replacement;
- automatic type checking in IDE;
- browserslist for browser targeting;
- npm scripts for build/dev/test workflows.

Deployment:
- project configured for Vercel deployment with SPA routing support;
- vercel.json configuration for proper index.html fallback;
- environment variables managed via Vercel dashboard;
- production build optimized for minimal bundle size.

vinylStore.description:
Vinyl Haven is a full-stack vinyl marketplace (frontend part of a team project).

Vinyl Haven is a modern online platform for buying and selling vinyl records, built by a team for the CIS market. I was responsible for full frontend development, creating an intuitive interface with advanced features for both collectors and casual users. The project demonstrates teamwork, C#/.NET backend integration, and scalable enterprise-grade application development.

My contribution (Frontend Development):

Full UI/UX from scratch:
- built the frontend structure from initial setup to production-ready state;
- created an adaptive component system with a minimalist visual direction;
- implemented Header with dynamic navigation and user-state indicators;
- built Footer with multilingual links and clear information architecture.

Landing and informational pages:
- Home page as a complete pre-landing with hero section, featured collections, and CTA;
- About page describing project concept and platform advantages;
- Contact page with feedback forms;
- Policy page for privacy policy and user agreements.

Catalog and filtering system:
- interactive vinyl catalog with product cards;
- advanced filtering by genre, artist, release year, and price;
- detailed Card pages with full release information;
- backend API integration for dynamic data loading.

Authentication and role-based access:
- Login page with registration/login flows;
- role-based pages for buyer/seller/admin;
- protected routes with redirects based on authentication status;
- C# backend integration for JWT tokens and session management.

E-commerce functionality:
- shopping cart with quantity management;
- wishlist for saving interesting releases;
- integration with backend order-processing endpoints;
- order state tracking.

Internationalization (i18next):
- full EN/RU support via react-i18next;
- dynamic language switch with persistence in localStorage;
- localized JSON files for all interface text;
- SEO-friendly multilingual approach.

Theme system (Light/Dark Mode):
- theme switch between light and dark modes;
- persistent theme selection via localStorage;
- CSS variables for all color tokens;
- smooth transitions during theme changes;
- adaptation to user system preferences.

Animations and UX enhancements:
- CSS/SCSS animations for smooth state transitions;
- skeleton loaders for better perceived performance;
- scroll animations and entrance effects;
- hover states and micro-interactions for improved engagement.

Infinite Scroll:
- infinite catalog scrolling with lazy product loading;
- Intersection Observer API for element visibility detection;
- optimized rendering for large lists;
- loading indicators and error handling.

Backend integration (C# .NET API):
- configured all API endpoints for backend communication;
- worked with RESTful API via fetch/axios;
- handled async requests and error states;
- PostgreSQL integration through backend layer;
- Vite proxy setup for development and production;
- migration from local backend to production server (Railway);
- RTK Query refactoring for improved data fetching.

Key technical solutions:

TypeScript and type safety:
- full typing for components, props, and API responses;
- strict TypeScript configuration for early error detection;
- interfaces for domain models (VinylRecord, Customer, Order);
- typed Redux store and actions.

Redux Toolkit state management:
- centralized state management via RTK;
- RTK Query for efficient data fetching and caching;
- slices for cart, wishlist, and authentication;
- optimistic UI updates;
- automatic cache invalidation on changes.

SCSS and modular styling architecture:
- SCSS for advanced styling capabilities;
- breakpoint mixins for responsive design (@use './breakpoints');
- modular styling approach (text.scss, buttons.scss, inputs.scss);
- CSS custom properties for theming;
- mobile-first approach with adaptive components;
- utility classes for repeated patterns.

React Router v6 navigation:
- custom HistoryRouter for programmatic navigation;
- ScrollToTop component for scroll restoration;
- protected routes with role-based access control;
- lazy-loaded pages for code splitting.

Vite bundler configuration:
- optimized Vite configuration for dev and production;
- proxy setup for API requests in development;
- environment variables through loadEnv;
- auto-reload and HMR for faster development;
- production build optimization with minification.

Notification system:
- context provider for global notifications;
- toast notifications for user feedback;
- error boundary for graceful error handling.

Performance optimizations:
- lazy loading of components and routes;
- memoization via useMemo and useCallback;
- list virtualization for large catalogs;
- image optimization and lazy loading;
- route-based code splitting.

Cross-browser compatibility:
- ESLint configuration for code quality;
- support for modern and legacy browsers through Babel;
- accessibility best practices (jsx-a11y);
- React hooks rules via eslint-plugin-react-hooks.

Deployment and DevOps:
- production build setup with Vite;
- Railway integration for backend hosting;
- environment-based configuration (dev/prod);
- CORS setup for cross-origin requests;
- reverse proxy configuration for API;
- production issue debugging with source maps.

Team collaboration:
- teamwork using Git feature branches;
- code reviews and pull request workflow;
- synchronization with backend developers on API contracts;
- documentation for components and API integrations;
- adherence to coding standards and best practices.

Important:
- backend server is currently unavailable, so some online features may not work in the demo.

pet.description:
Pet Care Project is a TypeScript/SCSS landing page built with a mobile-first approach.

Pet Care Project is a modern responsive landing page developed with a strong focus on mobile-first design and built on a modern technology stack. The project demonstrates the ability to build high-quality static websites with advanced typing and modular styling architecture.

Implemented functionality:

Mobile-First Architecture:
- design optimized for mobile devices first;
- responsive layout with smooth scaling on desktop;
- touch-friendly interface with optimized hit zones;
- progressive enhancement for larger screens.

Advanced SCSS Architecture:
- modular styling system with 38.5% project share;
- SCSS features usage (variables, mixins, nesting);
- dedicated styles/ directory for style organization;
- custom typography with self-hosted fonts (fonts/).

TypeScript-First Approach:
- full typing of components (60.7% TypeScript);
- strict tsconfig.json configuration;
- type-safe development experience;
- early error detection at compile time.

Modern Build Setup:
- Vite as bundler for instant build workflow;
- optimized production build;
- tree-shaking and code splitting;
- hot module replacement for fast development.

Key technical solutions:

Vite Build System:
- custom vite.config.ts configuration;
- production assets optimization;
- minimal build and reload time;
- modern ES modules approach.

TypeScript Configuration:
- strict typing via tsconfig.json;
- target and module settings for optimal output;
- path aliases for convenient module imports.

Responsive Design:
- mobile-first CSS approach;
- fluid typography and spacing;
- adaptive breakpoints for all devices;
- optimized images through public/.

Font Management:
- custom fonts in dedicated fonts/ directory;
- optimized loading through font-display;
- fallback strategies for web fonts.

Project Structure:
- clear src/ separation for source code;
- styles/ for global styles and theme;
- public/ for static assets;
- modular code organization.

Deployment:
- Vercel setup via vercel.json;
- optimized production build;
- SPA routing support through configuration;
- automatic deploy on push to main branch.

beats.description:
Beats Landing is a mobile-first product page built with TypeScript and pure CSS.

Beats Landing is a minimalist product landing page designed with a mobile-first approach for showcasing audio products. The project stands out with a balanced stack of TypeScript (47%) and pure CSS (51%), demonstrating the ability to build modern websites without styling frameworks, with a focus on performance and code clarity.

Implemented functionality:

Mobile-First Design Philosophy:
- responsive layout optimized primarily for smartphones;
- smooth scaling to tablet and desktop without quality loss;
- optimized touch targets for mobile devices;
- fluid typography and responsive spacing system.

Pure CSS Architecture (51%):
- no CSS-in-JS or preprocessors, pure CSS only;
- modern CSS features (CSS Grid, Flexbox, Custom Properties);
- dedicated styles/ directory for modular organization;
- CSS modules or BEM methodology usage;
- cross-browser compatibility without extra dependencies.

TypeScript Integration (47%):
- strict typing for all interactive components;
- type-safe event handlers and DOM manipulations;
- separate tsconfig.json and tsconfig.node.json configurations;
- TypeScript used for build scripts and tooling.

Product Showcase Features:
- hero section with product visualization;
- product specs and characteristics;
- image gallery with interactive elements;
- call-to-action blocks for conversion.

Modern Development Setup:
- Vite as an ultra-fast bundler;
- ESLint for code quality and consistency;
- hot module replacement for fast development;
- optimized production build with minification.

Key technical solutions:

Vanilla CSS Mastery:
- CSS Custom Properties for theming;
- CSS Grid for complex layouts;
- Flexbox for flexible components;
- media queries for responsive breakpoints;
- CSS animations without JavaScript overhead;
- progressive enhancement approach.

TypeScript Configuration:
- strict typing via tsconfig.json;
- separate config for Node.js scripts (tsconfig.node.json);
- ES module output for modern browsers;
- strict mode for maximum type safety.

Vite Build System:
- custom vite.config.ts configuration;
- asset optimization and code splitting;
- dev server with instant HMR;
- production build with tree-shaking.

Project Structure:
- clear src/ separation for source code;
- styles/ for CSS modules and global styles;
- public/ for static assets (images, fonts);
- modular architecture for scalability.

Code Quality:
- ESLint configuration for TypeScript;
- consistent code style;
- automated linting in development workflow;
- pre-commit hooks for code quality.

Performance Optimization:
- minimal JavaScript for better performance;
- CSS-only animations where possible;
- lazy loading of images;
- optimized assets via Vite;
- small bundle size due to no heavy libraries.

Responsive Images:
- adaptive images via picture element;
- optimization for different screen densities (1x, 2x);
- WebP with JPEG/PNG fallback;
- lazy loading for above-the-fold content.

Deployment:
- Vercel setup through vercel.json;
- SPA routing configuration;
- optimized production build;
- automatic deployment on push to main branch;
- environment-based configuration.

Approach advantages:

Vanilla CSS Benefits:
- zero runtime dependencies for styles;
- maximum performance;
- full styling control without abstractions;
- smaller bundle size;
- better understanding of CSS fundamentals.

TypeScript Safety:
- early error detection;
- improved developer experience with autocomplete;
- self-documenting code via types;
- safer refactoring.

Mobile-First Advantages:
- better performance on mobile devices;
- progressive enhancement for desktop;
- forced prioritization of important content;
- improved accessibility.

nike.description:
Nike Product Slider is an interactive web component that showcases a modern product slider inspired by premium brand design. The project demonstrates a strong understanding of building visually engaging user interfaces with smooth animations and responsive behavior.

Implemented functionality:
- full-screen slider using CSS viewport-relative units (100vw / 100vh);
- smooth transitions between slides with autoplay support;
- manual navigation via left/right arrow controls;
- layered typography effects (filled + outlined text) for visual depth;
- animated shadows and floating effects for product images;
- interactive rating system (stars) with fill logic up to the selected position;
- functional BUY NOW button with a dynamic cart counter;
- adaptive layout for all device sizes with dedicated breakpoints.

Key technical solutions:
- responsiveness: CSS Grid and Flexbox are used to create a flexible layout that adapts to any screen size;
- performance: Vite provides fast builds and optimized asset loading;
- UX: smooth CSS transitions and animations deliver natural interactions without lag;
- state management: JavaScript logic controls current slide, counters, and animation states.

Deployment:
 project is configured for automatic deployment to GitHub Pages via npm scripts.

energo.description:
Energy Construction is an HTML landing page with Owl Carousel and SVG iconography.

Energy Construction is a classic corporate landing page for a construction company, built on core web technologies without modern UI frameworks. The project demonstrates strong vanilla JavaScript skills, advanced CSS usage, and integration of popular jQuery plugins to deliver a professional business website.

Implemented functionality:

Owl Carousel integration:
- interactive sliders for showcasing projects and services;
- responsive carousel with touch support for mobile devices;
- autoplay with configurable intervals;
- navigation via dots and arrows;
- smooth transitions between slides;
- lazy loading of images for performance optimization.

SVG iconography system:
- scalable vector icons via SVG sprites;
- SVG fonts for consistent iconography;
- icon styling through CSS;
- reduced file size with SVG optimization;
- accessibility support via ARIA labels;
- retina-ready graphics with no quality loss.

Corporate content structure:
- hero section with compelling headline and CTA;
- About section with company story and mission;
- completed projects portfolio with gallery;
- services list with detailed descriptions;
- contact form for lead generation;
- footer with contact details and social links.

Responsive design:
- adaptive layout for all device types;
- mobile-first or desktop-first implementation;
- breakpoints for phones, tablets, and desktop;
- optimized images for different resolutions.

Key technical solutions:

HTML semantic markup (43.6%):
- semantic HTML5 tags (header, nav, section, article, footer);
- proper heading hierarchy (h1-h6) for SEO;
- accessibility-friendly markup;
- social sharing meta tags (Open Graph, Twitter Cards);
- structured data for search engines.

CSS architecture (53.2%):
- modular styling organization;
- CSS methodology usage (e.g., BEM or OOCSS);
- CSS Grid and Flexbox for layouts;
- custom CSS variables for theming;
- media queries for responsive breakpoints;
- CSS animations and transitions for smooth UX;
- cross-browser compatibility with vendor prefixes.

Vanilla JavaScript (3.2%):
- minimal but effective JS logic;
- Owl Carousel initialization and config;
- form handling and validation;
- smooth scrolling for anchor links;
- mobile menu toggle functionality;
- lazy-loading implementation.

jQuery & Owl Carousel:
- jQuery as dependency for Owl Carousel;
- carousel configuration (responsive, autoplay, loop);
- custom navigation element styling;
- event callbacks for interaction tracking;
- synchronization of multiple carousels when needed.

SVG icon system:
- SVG sprite technique for icon reuse;
- inline SVG for critical icons;
- external SVG files for better caching;
- fallback strategies for older browsers;
- CSS-based colorization via fill and stroke.

Performance optimization:
- HTML, CSS, and JavaScript minification;
- image optimization (compression, WebP);
- lazy loading for below-the-fold content;
- critical CSS inline for faster first paint;
- async/defer script strategy;
- CDN usage for popular libraries (jQuery, Owl Carousel).

SEO optimization:
- correct heading hierarchy;
- alt attributes for all images;
- meta description and keywords;
- Open Graph markup for social media;
- semantic HTML for better indexing;
- mobile-friendly design (important ranking factor).

Browser compatibility:
- support for modern browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge);
- graceful degradation for older versions;
- CSS autoprefixer for vendor prefixes;
- polyfills for newer JavaScript features.

Contact form:
- client-side validation in JavaScript;
- user-friendly error messages;
- spam protection (e.g., honeypot or reCAPTCHA);
- AJAX submission without page reload;
- success/error states for user feedback.

Project structure:

Typical file organization:
- index.html as main page;
- css/ for styles (optionally split into modules);
- js/ for scripts and libraries;
- images/ for optimized project visuals;
- fonts/ for SVG fonts and icon fonts;
- assets/ for additional resources.

Deployment:

Simple static hosting strategy:
- hosting on GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel;
- minimal server requirements;
- fast loading due to static nature;
- easy maintenance and updates;
- CDN for global delivery.

indonesia.description:
Indonesia Landing is a static HTML/CSS page with fixed dimensions.

Indonesia Landing is a static landing page built with pure HTML and CSS, without JavaScript frameworks and without responsive behavior. The project demonstrates a classic web design approach with a fixed-width layout, focused on desktop resolutions and pixel-perfect implementation.

Implemented functionality:

Fixed-Width Layout:
- fixed container width (typically 960px, 1024px, or 1200px);
- centered content positioning on the page;
- static element sizes without a fluid approach;
- pixel-perfect implementation of the design layout;
- focus on desktop resolutions (1280px+).

Indonesia theme:
- visual presentation of Indonesian culture/tourism;
- hero section with expressive imagery;
- informational blocks about landmarks;
- photo gallery or feature section;
- typography reflecting an exotic visual theme.

CSS-Driven Design (61.1%):
- styling-heavy implementation over markup complexity;
- detailed styling of each element;
- CSS used for all visual effects;
- possible use of CSS Grid/Flexbox for layouts;
- CSS hover effects and transitions;
- careful spacing and typography tuning.

Semantic HTML (38.9%):
- clean HTML markup without JavaScript logic;
- structured content via semantic tags;
- proper heading hierarchy;
- accessibility-friendly markup;
- SEO-oriented structure.

Key technical solutions:

Fixed-Width Architecture:
- fixed-width container (for example, .container { width: 1200px; margin: 0 auto; });
- no media queries and responsive breakpoints;
- static font sizes in px;
- fixed image sizes;
- predictable layout across desktop monitors.

CSS Styling Approach:
- possible CSS methodology usage (BEM, OOCSS);
- modular styling organization by sections;
- CSS reset or normalize for cross-browser consistency;
- float-based or modern Grid/Flexbox layouts;
- CSS-only decorative elements;
- gradients, shadows, and border-radius for visual depth.

Typography System:
- fixed font sizes;
- clear heading hierarchy with explicit sizing;
- web-safe fonts or @font-face setup;
- line-height and letter-spacing for readability;
- color scheme for text content.

Layout Structure:
- traditional structure: header, main sections, footer;
- multi-column content layouts;
- optional sidebar for additional information;
- grid-based alignment system;
- clear separation of visual zones.

Image Integration:
- static images with fixed dimensions;
- background-image for decorative elements;
- image sprites for icons (where needed);
- optimized file sizes;
- alt attributes for accessibility.

CSS Effects & Enhancements:
- hover states for interactive elements;
- CSS transitions for smooth interactions;
- box-shadow for depth;
- gradient backgrounds for visual interest;
- pseudo-elements (::before, ::after) for decoration;
- CSS-only buttons and navigation.

Cross-Browser Compatibility:
- vendor prefixes for CSS properties;
- fallback styles for older browsers;
- CSS reset for consistency;
- testing in common browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge).

Performance Considerations:
- minimal page weight without JavaScript;
- optimized CSS files;
- compressed images;
- reduced number of HTTP requests;
- fast initial page load.
